00:33:03.090 --> 00:33:05.400
is being applied to agriculture.

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:10.950
And so when fertilizing
machines, or seeding machines,

00:33:10.950 --> 00:33:16.390
are going over a
piece of terrain,

00:33:16.390 --> 00:33:18.720
there's information
about the chemistry

00:33:18.720 --> 00:33:22.660
of the soil that they're passing
over, the fertility of it.

00:33:22.660 --> 00:33:29.790
And so in real time,
with this technology,

00:33:29.790 --> 00:33:32.340
a single driver could
be passing over.

00:33:32.340 --> 00:33:35.550
And the field has
been mapped as to what

00:33:35.550 --> 00:33:40.320
needs more of one chemical,
what part of the field

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:43.670
needs more of one
chemical than another.

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:49.350
And so you don't just apply
the same coating of everything

00:33:49.350 --> 00:33:50.310
everywhere.

00:33:50.310 --> 00:33:52.110
But it's really customized.

00:33:52.110 --> 00:33:53.909
I mean, that never--

00:33:53.909 --> 00:33:55.200
SUSAN ROCKEFELLER: That's huge.

00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:56.866
DAVID ROCKEFELLER JR:
--happened before.

00:33:56.866 --> 00:34:00.330
And so it's a wonderful
way in which technology is

00:34:00.330 --> 00:34:02.020
helping the production of food.

00:34:02.020 --> 00:34:06.720
In fact, you might say that both
of these technological examples

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:11.015
are ultimately about
healthy food for us humans.

00:34:11.015 --> 00:34:13.620
SUSAN ROCKEFELLER: And it's
