00:52:45.610 --> 00:52:46.160
So--

00:52:46.160 --> 00:52:47.915
AUDIENCE: You were
first if you want to.

00:52:47.915 --> 00:52:48.540
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:52:48.540 --> 00:52:49.749
I just have a quick question.

00:52:49.749 --> 00:52:51.373
My name's Matt, a
long-time New Yorker,

00:52:51.373 --> 00:52:52.910
so I've always grown
up appreciating

00:52:52.910 --> 00:52:55.840
everything you've done for
the community in New York.

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:58.700
I actually had a
question about art.

00:52:58.700 --> 00:53:00.700
You hear and read
more and more today,

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:04.970
and I'm sure you guys
see it, that art is now

00:53:04.970 --> 00:53:07.700
being touted as an
investment vehicle

00:53:07.700 --> 00:53:11.120
more so than ever
previously before.

00:53:11.120 --> 00:53:14.480
And I'm curious as to what
you guys think, and see,

00:53:14.480 --> 00:53:16.760
and in the circles
that you guys run in,

00:53:16.760 --> 00:53:22.910
in terms of, is this a positive
or a negative effect in the art

00:53:22.910 --> 00:53:25.670
world, where folks are now
looking at art as something

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:28.160
that can appreciate, rather
than just the ability

00:53:28.160 --> 00:53:29.810
to appreciate art.

00:53:29.810 --> 00:53:34.390
And what's this going to
do to art in the long term?

00:53:34.390 --> 00:53:35.640
DAVID ROCKEFELLER JR: Big one.

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:37.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:37.510 --> 00:53:42.060
Well, there are pluses
and minuses, I would say.

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:44.850
I mean, for me, the most
important thing about art

00:53:44.850 --> 00:53:51.240
is its ability to move us, to
impel us to greater heights,

00:53:51.240 --> 00:53:55.650
to help us look into
the human condition, all

00:53:55.650 --> 00:53:57.280
the wonderful things
that art does.

00:53:57.280 --> 00:54:02.760
And I'm talking about not only
visual arts, but all the arts.

00:54:02.760 --> 00:54:07.130
On the other hand, as
art in the visual field

00:54:07.130 --> 00:54:09.930
has gotten so expensive,
it puts it out

00:54:09.930 --> 00:54:11.910
of reach of a lot of people.

00:54:11.910 --> 00:54:15.270
You can only have
so much in museums.

00:54:15.270 --> 00:54:19.650
And I think it, for some
people, does make art

00:54:19.650 --> 00:54:23.940
a commodity instead of a
great human expression.

00:54:23.940 --> 00:54:28.140
So I think that it's wonderful
for the artists who are selling

00:54:28.140 --> 00:54:31.950
their art at great prices
and dispiriting for those who

00:54:31.950 --> 00:54:32.790
don't.

00:54:32.790 --> 00:54:34.470
There's so many
things in our culture

00:54:34.470 --> 00:54:37.350
where the split between
the highest and the lowest

00:54:37.350 --> 00:54:38.070
is so great.

00:54:38.070 --> 00:54:40.840
And art now has become
one of those areas,

00:54:40.840 --> 00:54:45.810
you know, professional sports,
corporate executives, whatever.

00:54:45.810 --> 00:54:47.670
So it's another example of that.

00:54:47.670 --> 00:54:53.610
And that part of the equation,
Christie's benefits from.

00:54:53.610 --> 00:54:56.460
Our auction benefited us from.

00:54:56.460 --> 00:55:02.100
But is that piece of art
one million times better

00:55:02.100 --> 00:55:06.240
than that piece of art just
because the price says so?

00:55:06.240 --> 00:55:07.950
Not necessarily.

00:55:07.950 --> 00:55:10.470
JONATHAN RENDELL: I think
individual ownership is not

00:55:10.470 --> 00:55:14.310
necessarily the way in which
you should judge a work of art.

00:55:14.310 --> 00:55:15.800
DAVID ROCKEFELLER
JR: Here, here.

00:55:15.800 --> 00:55:17.850
JONATHAN RENDELL:
That some people like

00:55:17.850 --> 00:55:20.930
to own very expensive objects.

00:55:20.930 --> 00:55:23.340
And there will always
be those people.

00:55:23.340 --> 00:55:26.010
Thank god, because
that pays my bills.

00:55:26.010 --> 00:55:32.400
But it's equally possible to
get that feeling of elevation

00:55:32.400 --> 00:55:35.760
that a great work of
art conveys to you

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:38.130
by going to see it in
a museum, by looking

00:55:38.130 --> 00:55:39.840
at a great piece
of architecture,

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:41.924
by listening to music.

00:55:41.924 --> 00:55:43.590
I mean, there are so
many different ways

00:55:43.590 --> 00:55:49.180
that are not to do with the
capitalization of the object.

00:55:49.180 --> 00:55:52.463
So I think we live in a very--

00:55:52.463 --> 00:55:56.790
I live in a very rarefied
world in which people spend

00:55:56.790 --> 00:55:58.740
a lot of money on objects.

00:55:58.740 --> 00:56:00.720
Do I identify myself
in that world?

00:56:00.720 --> 00:56:03.320
No, not necessarily.

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:05.940
I am equally happy
going to a museum

00:56:05.940 --> 00:56:08.071
and looking at an object.

00:56:08.071 --> 00:56:10.320
And I too have visitation
rights on some of the things

00:56:10.320 --> 00:56:12.300
I've sold in the
past at museums.

00:56:12.300 --> 00:56:15.780
And that's a huge satisfaction
because you've put

00:56:15.780 --> 00:56:17.970
something in the public arena.

00:56:17.970 --> 00:56:22.470
So I think that the art market
is not necessarily related

00:56:22.470 --> 00:56:25.670
to the true art world.

00:56:25.670 --> 00:56:28.750
SUSAN ROCKEFELLER: Can I just
say that you can go to museums.

00:56:28.750 --> 00:56:30.220
No, I thought that
was very good.

00:56:30.220 --> 00:56:33.200
But also, I think it's great
just to go to galleries.

00:56:33.200 --> 00:56:34.330
Go to the Lower East Side.

00:56:34.330 --> 00:56:35.020
Go to Brooklyn.

00:56:35.020 --> 00:56:37.780
Go look, and train your eye.

00:56:37.780 --> 00:56:42.160
And if you like something, I
mean, there's a lot of art.

00:56:42.160 --> 00:56:44.360
This is about emerging art.

00:56:44.360 --> 00:56:46.570
And you could make
a small contribution

00:56:46.570 --> 00:56:51.830
to someone's art career that
can totally change their lives.

00:56:51.830 --> 00:56:55.990
And I agree with you that
some art has this crazy price

00:56:55.990 --> 00:56:56.680
tag to it.

00:56:56.680 --> 00:56:59.420
And then there's other artists
that are unbelievably talented.

00:56:59.420 --> 00:57:02.410
They will never-- well, maybe.

00:57:02.410 --> 00:57:04.030
Doubtful that many
of them will ever

00:57:04.030 --> 00:57:07.960
get to the heights of some of
those that were auctioned off.

00:57:07.960 --> 00:57:10.780
But that doesn't mean that they
aren't unbelievably talented,

00:57:10.780 --> 00:57:13.090
and that you can enjoy
looking at the pieces.

00:57:13.090 --> 00:57:16.420
So I'm one for really
looking at emerging arts.

00:57:16.420 --> 00:57:18.500
And we support arts
whenever we travel.

00:57:18.500 --> 00:57:19.690
We will buy something.

00:57:19.690 --> 00:57:21.790
And it can be ceramic.

00:57:21.790 --> 00:57:23.050
It could be a carving.

00:57:23.050 --> 00:57:27.610
It could be something that's
been repurposed from Coca-Cola

00:57:27.610 --> 00:57:30.190
cans, sort of upcycled art.

00:57:30.190 --> 00:57:33.730
And then those become some
of the memories of our lives.

00:57:33.730 --> 00:57:36.610
And if they end up
having value, great.

00:57:36.610 --> 00:57:38.510
But we love living with them.

00:57:38.510 --> 00:57:39.010
So--

00:57:39.010 --> 00:57:41.700
DAVID ROCKEFELLER
JR: That's nice.

00:57:41.700 --> 00:57:43.742
EMMA FALLONE: Then
really quickly.

00:57:43.742 --> 00:57:45.200
AUDIENCE: My question
was answered.

00:57:45.200 --> 00:57:47.760
EMMA FALLONE: All right, well,
that's a pretty fabulous note

00:57:47.760 --> 00:57:48.259
to end on.

00:57:48.259 --> 00:57:50.877
Does anyone have
any final thoughts?

00:57:50.877 --> 00:57:52.710
DAVID ROCKEFELLER JR:
Thanks for being here.

00:57:52.710 --> 00:57:54.160
EMMA FALLONE: Well, then,
thanks so much for being here.

00:57:54.160 --> 00:57:55.060
And thank you.

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:58.410
[APPLAUSE]

